  "analysis": "Purpose declarations are a new top-level construct for Reify, similar in structure to traits/structures but with distinct semantics: they bind entity references (not values) via parameters, support reflective schema queries on those entities, and can be activated/deactivated to inject/remove constraints and objectives from the evaluation graph.\n\nThe implementation follows the established pattern for adding new language constructs (as seen in traits, fields, ports, connect/chain):\n\n1. **Grammar**: Add `purpose_declaration` to `_declaration` in grammar.js, with `purpose_param` and `purpose_member` rules. The `purpose_member` reuses existing `constraint_declaration`, `let_declaration`, `minimize_declaration`, `maximize_declaration`, and `guarded_block` rules. After grammar change, regenerate parser.c via `tree-sitter generate`.\n\n2. **Parser (reify-syntax)**: Add `Declaration::Purpose(PurposeDef)` to the enum, define `PurposeDef` and `PurposeParam` AST types. Add lowering in `ts_parser.rs` following the trait/structure patterns (lower_purpose, lower_purpose_params, lower_purpose_members).\n\n3. **Compiler (reify-compiler)**: Add `CompiledPurpose` type containing compiled constraints, objectives, and reflective schema query results. Compile purposes in the `compile()` function's pre-pass section. Reflective schema queries (subject.params, subject.geometric_params, etc.) are resolved at compile-time by looking up the bound entity's TopologyTemplate.\n\n4. **Stdlib (reify-stdlib)**: Add determinacy predicates: `determined()`, `constrained()`, `undetermined()`, `partially_determined()`. These inspect DeterminacyState of value cells.\n\n5. **Eval (reify-eval)**: Add purpose activation/deactivation API on Engine. When activated, inject the purpose's compiled constraints/objectives into the evaluation graph; when deactivated, remove them.\n\nKey design consideration: Purposes bind entity references (Structure names), not instances. The reflective queries resolve at compile-time against the TopologyTemplate of the bound structure. Activation at eval-time injects constraints into a specific entity instance.\n\n## Review Fix Analysis\n\nFive blocking issues were identified during review:\n\n1. **api_contract_violation** (builders.rs) \u2014 ALREADY FIXED: `compiled_purposes: Vec::new()` is already present in CompiledModuleBuilder::build() at line 513. No action needed.\n\n2. **missing_assertion** (purpose_compile_tests.rs) \u2014 The `compile_module` helper only checks parse errors but not compile-level Severity::Error diagnostics. Fixed in steps 19-20.\n\n3. **state_consistency** (eval lib.rs) \u2014 Calling eval() a second time replaces eval_state with a fresh snapshot but doesn't clear active_purposes/active_objective_map. Fixed in steps 21-22.\n\n4. **data_loss_silent_failure** (compiler Let arm in compile_purpose) \u2014 The Let arm compiled the expression but discarded it. Fixed in steps 23-24 by emitting Severity::Error diagnostic.\n\n5. **data_loss_silent_failure** (compiler wildcard arm in compile_purpose) \u2014 The `_ => {}` catch-all at line 1434 silently discards all unhandled MemberDecl variants: GuardedGroup, Param, Sub, Port, Connect, Chain, and AssociatedType. The grammar's `purpose_member` reuses `guarded_block`, so a user can write a where-guarded constraint block in a purpose body \u2014 it parses successfully into MemberDecl::GuardedGroup but is silently dropped at compile time with no diagnostic. This is the same category of silent data loss as the Let issue fixed in step 24. Fix: replace the wildcard with explicit arms for each unhandled variant, each emitting a Severity::Error diagnostic. Steps 25-26.",
